Introduction

This tutorial will cover all the basic steps involved in lipidQuan visualization.

Data

The data for this tutorial will consist of the final output file containing the mol% pmol of species and classes.

Step 1: open LipidQuan

Start by open up LipidQuan. This can be done by doing these 3 steps:

  1. Open Rstudio

  2. Write âlibrary(lipidQuan)â

  3. Write ârunLipidQuan()â

If the web browser encounters problems doing any of the steps in the tutorial, LipidQuan can also be open by going to:

, open either ui.R or server.R and hit the Run button at the right top corner of Rstudio.

After this go to the visualization procedure tab.

Step 2: load data into LipidQuan

In the visualization procedure tab section, start by choosing the input file to be used by clicking on the âBrowseâ¦â button below âChoose a mol% final output file (.csv-file)â. For this tutorial we will be using the following two files:

  1. finalOutput_molPct.csv

  2. sampleTypes.csv

The two file is located in the following folder:

#> [1] "/data/user/andre/lipidomics/lipidQuan/inst/extdata"

Go to this folder and select the two files.

Step 3: choose sample type file

Next, we need to select the file containing information about the sample types. This is done by clicking on the âBrowseâ¦â button below âChoose a file containing sample type information for the dataâ.

Step 4: log2 transformation

Next, weâll choose to log2 transform our data by clicking on the checkbox âlog2 transformation of the dataâ. Weâll also set the pseudo counts added before the transformation to 0.0001 to avoid \(-\infty\) values in the transformed data.

Step 5: Select plot types

We now have to select the plot types that we want. In this analysis weâre both interested in a PCA biplot and a heatmap, so we click on both the âCreate PCA biplots of mol% classes and speciesâ and the âCreate heatmap plots of mol% classes and speciesâ checkboxes.

Step 6: clustering

Since we chose to create a heatmap which contains clustering, a specification of the amount of clusters is needed. In our case weâll not let any prior knowledge about the sample types determine the amount of clusters, so weâll not write any number in the âOptional selection of k clusters for the heatmapâ field. In this way weâll let the NbClust algortihm determine the most likely amount of clusters for the heatmap.

Step 7: Output folder

Lastly, the folder where the output files should be saved to has to be defined. Here weâll write the filepath to where we wish to save the files. The following describes how to obtain the full path:

From Mac OS X El Capitan 2015 onwards (As of February 2018): Go to the folder of interest, right click on the folder, press the alt button + click on âCopy âfolder-nameâ as Pathnameâ. Go back to LipidQuan and paste the folder path (â Command button + V) into the output folder field.

After this weâll press âCreate Plotsâ.
